english:
  title: Blue Petition at the Numinous Treasure Ritual Altar
  author: Kwon Geun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    First Offering

    You descend upon this altar, present at its side,
    Your presence vast and luminous as heaven itself.
    When sincerity dwells within the heart,
    It manifests without—there is no deception here.
    Like gentle wind that carries the morning,
    May you deign to savor the humble offerings laid before you.

    Second Offering

    From this gift we humbly partake of manifold blessings,
    Gazing upward at the boundless sky in reverent awe.
    With respectful ceremony twice performed and sincere libations poured,
    We deepen our devotion. Descend now and receive,
    Bring tranquility and flourishing, let all things thrive and prosper.

    Third Offering

    The Tao without sound or scent transcends all naming—
    Yet constant in beginning and in end, sincerity alone is precious.
    When we serve with ritual propriety, response follows,
    And connection is mysteriously achieved.

    Though I am small and unworthy, burdened with this realm's charge,
    Five years upon the throne have brought not one day's peace.
    Our armies strong, yet foreign foes advance without restraint,
    Our people wavering, suspicion breeding strife within.
    Great kingdoms demand tribute we cannot worthily render,
    Distant lands send envoys—how can we discern their truth?
    Our storehouses stand empty as suspended stones,
    While our fields know not even the smallest grain.
    The people walk barefoot and alone—alas, what sorrow this brings.

    Reflecting thus, my heart breaks.
    I have failed in compassion to nurture my flock,
    Yet shame fills me for bearing this shepherd's burden still.
    Truly, I must turn blame upon myself—
    Why seek fault elsewhere?
    All calamities that visit us arise from my own lack of virtue,
    Summoned by my unworthiness alone.

    Therefore I straighten my conduct and cultivate my nature,
    That I might transform these afflictions into auspicious signs.
    Following the true way, with utmost reverence and purity,
    I humbly lay this petition before the divine.

    May the spirits descend and witness!
    May they order the four directions,
    Placing our nation's foundation upon the immovable rock,
    That my lineage endure a hundred generations,
    Receiving the Emperor's blessings without end.
    May civil and military officials walk in harmony,
    May distant and near peoples join in accord,
    And the transformative power of music and song flourish once more,
    While the sound of weapons falls silent forever.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: This is a 'blue petition' (청사/青詞), a liturgical text recited during Daoist ritual offerings in three stages (초헌, 이헌, 삼헌). Written by Kwon Geun during his tenure as a high official in early Joseon, it reflects both Daoist cosmology and Confucian statecraft.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'three offerings' follow the traditional Daoist altar ceremony structure, with each section building in spiritual intensity and thematic depth.
  - key: ''
    value: Kwon Geun's allusions to military threats, internal discord, and fiscal exhaustion reflect the turbulent early decades of the Joseon dynasty.
